# Little's MCAR test
mcar_test(dat.wide)
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   statistic    df p.value missing.patterns
##       <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>            <int>
## 1      10.2    17   0.894                5
# p=0.89, so we can treat them as MCAR

# cancel the 3 ID with all missing SFD
miss3 <- dat.wide %>% 
  filter(is.na(SFD_1) & is.na(SFD_2) & is.na(SFD_3)) %>% 
  pull(ID)
dat_new = dat %>% 
  filter(!ID %in% miss3)

# cancel all with missing SFD
dat_no_missing = dat %>% 
  filter(!is.na(SFD))

# completer's ID
has_missing <- dat %>% 
  filter(is.na(SFD)) %>% 
  pull(ID)
dat_complete = dat %>% 
  filter(!ID %in% has_missing)
# Load the required package
library(glmmTMB)
## Warning in checkDepPackageVersion(dep_pkg = "TMB"): Package version inconsistency detected.
## glmmTMB was built with TMB version 1.9.10
## Current TMB version is 1.9.11
## Please re-install glmmTMB from source or restore original 'TMB' package (see '?reinstalling' for more information)
# Assuming your data is in a dataframe called 'data'
# and the variables are named as they appear in your model output
model <- glmmTMB(cbind(SFD, 14 - SFD) ~ time + group + group*time + (1 | school/ID),
                 data = dat_complete,
                 family = betabinomial(link = "logit"),
                 ziformula = ~1)  # This is for zero-inflation, which appears to be near 1

# Print the summary of the model
summary(model)

library(glmmTMB)

# and the variables are named as they appear in your model output
model <- glmmTMB(cbind(SFD, 14 - SFD) ~ time + group + group*time + (1 | school/ID),
                 data = dat_new,
                 family = betabinomial(link = "logit"),
                 ziformula = ~1)  # This is for zero-inflation, which appears to be near 1

# Print the summary of the model
